>UPI Fraud in India

One of the most prevalent cybercrimes in India is UPI (Unified Payments Interface) fraud, in which perpetrators deceive users into sending money or disclosing private banking information. On websites like OLX, scammers often pretend to be bank employees, delivery drivers, or buyers.

Typically, the fraud occurs in stages: Initially, the con artist calls, texts, or uses WhatsApp to contact the victim and instills a sense of urgency (e.g., "Your account will be blocked" or "Scan this QR to receive payment"). They then send a malicious QR code or payment request. The victim completes the transaction without realizing that scanning or approving a request actually sends money rather than receives it. Scammers occasionally request PINs or OTPs as well.
Due to their potential ignorance of such scams, college students and new digital users are often targeted. Financial loss, psychological strain, and compromised bank accounts are just a few of the dire repercussions. Victims have lost thousands to lakhs of rupees in a matter of minutes in some actual incidents that have been reported throughout India.

This emphasizes the significance of being digitally aware, confirming requests, and never disclosing private financial information online.

